When we talk about how to perform a great looking squat, we often discuss things like keeping your knees in line with stable feet and a balanced descent into the bottom – but what most don’t discuss is the importance of the start position. 
.
When I refer to the start position, I’m talking about the quality of your posture standing with the barbell on your back and the actions you take before you start the descent. 
.
For example, when you take the bar out of the rack, I often see many athletes incorrectly shrug up on the bar. This places a lot of excessive pressure on your neck and makes it difficult to stabilize the bar when you start getting fatigued. Instead, pull your shoulder blades together and down as you wedge yourself against the bar. 
.
So instead of having a ton of over – activity in your upper traps, we want to focus in on creating as much stiffness and muscle contraction in the mid and low trap and lats. 
.
By doing this correctly, you will create a nice shelf for the barbell to sit on as you walk the bar back out of the rack. Once you get your stance set, take a huge breath and brace your core. You can see Lee’s stomach expand into his belt as he takes inhales before slowly starting his squat by hinging his hips back and only then going into his descent. 
.
By solidifying stiffness and stability in your start position, you set yourself up for a more efficient squat pattern.🙌🏼
.

In order for the hips to sink deep when you squat, you need the knees to translate forward towards the toes – this requires sufficient ankle mobility. The joint connection of the talus bone and tibia must move unrestricted and the muscles on the backside of the calf (like the larger gastric and smaller soleus) must be flexible enough to allow your shin to move forward.
.
To test this mobility, I had him try the 5” wall test – and as you can see he was unable to hit the wall with his knee without his heel popping off the ground – illuminating his problem!
.
I recommended he start with these 3 ankle mobility drills: 20 reps of a banded joint mobilizations with the band placed on top of the talus bone just under the larger ankle bones holding the end position for 3 seconds before coming back. Then 3 sets of 30 seconds on a box calf stretch – driving the knee over the toes until it brings out a good stretch in the back of the calf/achilles tendon area. He followed this with a deep goblet squat stretch, swiveling one knee at a time over the toes until a good stretch is found in the back of the calf again. This is a great “position specific” stretch as it works to improve ankle mobility in a deep squat position we’re trying to improve. .
After adding these into his warm up he noted an ability to squat deeper as you can see and felt more comfortable in his bottom position with weight on his back. Here’s a before and after with similar weight. Great work Jared!
.

Don’t fear flexion, understand it. Let’s talk about context.
.
If we look deep in your spine each disc has an inner nucleus that is surrounded by layers of collagen rings held together by a ground substance✅
.
Gymnasts focus a lot of their core work with exercises that move the spine through full ranges. Because there is low amounts of load with spinal movement, their spines stay flexible and resilient to safely handle skill work that requires forced end range of flexion.🤸🏼‍♀️
.
In order for powerlifters to lift massive weights and maintain the integrity of the spine, the spine must be held stable. This stiffness allows for resiliency with high loads. For this reason, strength athletes should perform isometric core exercises with the goal to resist excessive movement.✅
.
If the powerlifter trained like the gymnast, allowing the back to round under load over and over again, they weaken disc structure, increasing risk of a disc bulge  as the nucleus becomes pressurized under compression and works its ways through cracks in the rings.❌Does this mean everyone who rounds their back in a deadlift instantly is going to get a disc bulge? No, but the risk is increased the more load and the more reps someone performs.📝
.
So when someone asks, is all spinal flexion dangerous? Say, "it depends." Is the spine loaded and what is the end goal of what the person is trying to build.✅
.
Big shout out to Dr. Dave Tilley @shift_movementscience for the collaboration in making today’s post, @3d4medical for the visual of the body from their complete anatomy app & the following athletes featured today: @kylie_gorgenyi, @sheepdawgst, @severin_irimia & @thevanillagorilla92

The stretch I'm demonstrating today is one of my favorite hip openers to use prior to squatting. It's a stretch I learned years ago from Kelly Starrett of @thereadystate. Keys for proper execution: keep your trail leg straight & lean from the hips (don't drop your chest as you lean forward). As always, test - retest to see if this mobility exercise is right for you! Sit into a deep squat. Notice how you feel. Then perform this stretch - and immediately sit into your squat after. If you felt like you could sit more comfortably in the deep squat position - this stretch was efficient for your body to help you get into better positions! 
.
To learn more of my other favorite hip mobility exercises, check out my YouTube video “Hip Mobility for a Perfect Squat.”📲

Today I want to show you why finding your individual movement diagnosis for shoulder pain is so important. Jerome came to me with shoulder pain when snatching - now traditional medial model will try to look at a scan of your shoulder and determine what they see as “abnormal” to be the exact cause of pain. In Jerome’s case they found a small tear in his labrum. However, abnormal findings on MRI do not always equal the exact cause of prin. In fact there is a lot of science to show people have these abnormal findings without any pain. One in particular showed close to 80% of major league pitchers had a labrum abnormality without pain! 
.
So what do we do when an athlete presents with pain? We don’t just try random exercises we see on social media – as there is no “one size fits all” approach for fixing injury. What we do is evaluate and assess to uncover the exact path to take.
.
If you’re dealing with shoulder issues & want to try some of the tests I use to figure out what to do next, start with my blog “How to screen your shoulder pain” on squatuniversity.com📲

If you're about to squat, deadlift, bench or perform any of the olympic lifts, you need to warm your shoulders up well. Doing so will help your body move as well as possible, put up big weight and decrease your risk of injury. Dan @drettenmaier came to me with knee pain that had been frustrating him for the past 5 years! In this video you’ll see his evaluation, part of his treatment & see how he’s doing today!
.
Takeaway: there is no one size fits all method to fixing knee pain. You must evaluate (especially looking at the area above & below the site of pain) and create an individualized plan to address what you find while slowly rebuilding capacity. Remember, a knees over toes position is nothing to fear! However we must understand context and sometimes need to take a step back in order to eventually move forward.
.

node.text:
When you’re born, your toes are the WIDEST part of your entire foot. It’s interesting that shoes made for babies and toddlers are usually shaped like those feet. Unfortunately once you get into kids & adult sizes - the large majority of shoes produced today are WAY TOO NARROW. They are no longer shaped like feet & therefore do way more harm than good! 
.
There are in fact MANY research articles showing that modern shoes that are made with a narrow toe box like this are the cause of foot issues like bunions, plantar fasciitis, Morton’s neuroma, etc. People who grow up in cultures that don’t wear these kinds of shoes maintain their natural foot shape they had at birth and have minimal foot issues as they age!
.
Unfortunately you won’t hear about this from major shoe brands as they want you to keep buying their fashion forward shoes. They don’t think people will buy foot shaped shoes. 
.
But times are changing. The consumer is becoming more educated & is starting to demand shoes that are doing less harm to their feet! 
.
Are you a part of this change?
.
Want to learn more? Start with my podcast “Why your shoes suck” with Dr. Ray McClanahan.📲
.
Shout out to @myfootfunction for their amazing graphics used in this post!

When we talk about how to perform a great looking squat, we often discuss things like keeping your knees in line with stable feet and a balanced descent into the bottom – but what most don’t discuss is the importance of the start position. 
.
When I refer to the start position, I’m talking about the quality of your posture standing with the barbell on your back and the actions you take before you start the descent. 
.
For example, when you take the bar out of the rack, I often see many athletes incorrectly shrug up on the bar. This places a lot of excessive pressure on your neck and makes it difficult to stabilize the bar when you start getting fatigued. Instead, pull your shoulder blades together and down as you wedge yourself against the bar. 
.
So instead of having a ton of over – activity in your upper traps, we want to focus in on creating as much stiffness and muscle contraction in the mid and low trap and lats. 
.
By doing this correctly, you will create a nice shelf for the barbell to sit on as you walk the bar back out of the rack. Once you get your stance set, take a huge breath and brace your core. You can see Lee’s stomach expand into his belt as he takes inhales before slowly starting his squat by hinging his hips back and only then going into his descent. 
.
By solidifying stiffness and stability in your start position, you set yourself up for a more efficient squat pattern.🙌🏼
.

In 1978 Harvard physician Dr. Gabe Mirkin coined the term RICE (Rest. Ice. Compression. Elevation.) as the recommended treatment for sports injuries. Since this time, the medical community has religiously used this protocol for the treatment of all acute injuries AND in the recovery of intense exercise. But here's the deal, just because the pain and soreness you experience is decreased temporarily with ice does NOT mean you’re fixing the problem. In fact, you actually may be doing more harm than good.🤯
.
What most don't realize is that in 2013 Dr. Gabe Mirkin came out and WITHDREW his original statement writing, “Subsequent research shows that ice can actually delay recovery. Mild movement helps tissue to heal faster, and the application of cold suppresses the immune responses that start and hasten recovery."❌
.
To read the full blog post (8-10 min read) on why ice is a bad idea after injury and in the recovery from intense exercise (including 30 cited research articles), check out “Dont Ice, Walk It Off” on SquatUniversity.com📲
.
Sure, if you’re in 10 out of 10 pain, some ice can be helpful to decrease pain. But, our goal should always be to treat the WHY behind pain and not try to cover it up by addressing the symptoms. 
.
So what would be a better choice than ice for Lebron here between games/practices? We dont always want to do MORE training as his body needs to recover as well. I’m a big fan of NMES devices for this reason (such as the @themarcpro) as it can help optimize recovery while you passively rest. It mimics active recovery bringing blood flow to the areas you need it & removes the bad (swelling & damaged cells) that comes with injury & intense training so you can optimize recovery rather than JUST take the symptoms away with ice.

In order for the hips to sink deep when you squat, you need the knees to translate forward towards the toes – this requires sufficient ankle mobility. The joint connection of the talus bone and tibia must move unrestricted and the muscles on the backside of the calf (like the larger gastric and smaller soleus) must be flexible enough to allow your shin to move forward.
.
To test this mobility, I had him try the 5” wall test – and as you can see he was unable to hit the wall with his knee without his heel popping off the ground – illuminating his problem!
.
I recommended he start with these 3 ankle mobility drills: 20 reps of a banded joint mobilizations with the band placed on top of the talus bone just under the larger ankle bones holding the end position for 3 seconds before coming back. Then 3 sets of 30 seconds on a box calf stretch – driving the knee over the toes until it brings out a good stretch in the back of the calf/achilles tendon area. He followed this with a deep goblet squat stretch, swiveling one knee at a time over the toes until a good stretch is found in the back of the calf again. This is a great “position specific” stretch as it works to improve ankle mobility in a deep squat position we’re trying to improve. .
After adding these into his warm up he noted an ability to squat deeper as you can see and felt more comfortable in his bottom position with weight on his back. Here’s a before and after with similar weight. Great work Jared!
.

node.text:
Did you know you can use this box stretch to hit your thoracic spine or your lats? But why would you use either?🤔
.
In order to show good technique when lifting, we ideally want to see a flat back. This requires an certain amount of thoracic spine mobility. If you want to get your elbows up on a front squat or your arms in a good position over your head, you need a certain amount of lat flexibility.📝
.
But how do you know which one to use🤔
.
To screen your mid-back, tape an X on the ground and sit in the middle with a PVC pipe across your chest. Rotate as far as you can each way. If you can’t move to at least 45 degrees, we need to work on t-spine mobility by arching the mid back as you sink your chest towards the floor during the box stretch.✅
.
To screen your lats, have a friend raise your arm as high as possible over your head with your palm up towards the sky. Then internally rotate the arm & do the same with the palm facing down. If you had less range of motion this time, it means we need to work on lat flexibility by placing your arms in a “V” position and rounding your back and tucking your hips under during the box stretch.✅
.
Regardless of which one you decide to perform, try 5 for a 10 second hold and then re-test the earlier screen to see if you were able to make any significant change.🙌🏼
.
